    "R. Alan Culpepper": "Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` has already demonstrated\nhis authority in teaching and in exorcisms (1:22, 27; 2:10). Now he\ncommissions the disciples as his emissaries, to carry his authority with\nthem. In an era when business required that emissaries be able to travel\nand represent one\u2019s interests, the rabbinic ruling was that \u201ca man\u2019s agent\n[v_2Ch_17_7] [v_2Ch_17_8] [v_2Ch_17_9] is like to himself\u201d (m. Berakoth 5.5; cf. 2 Chr 17:7-9; John `[char_John_Ref]` 13:16). See\nthe discussion of \u201cunclean spirits\u201d in the commentary and connections\n[v_Mrk_1_23] on Mark 1:23 above.\nJesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 instructions regarding what the disciples should and should not\ntake with them ensure that they will travel by faith, depending on God\nto provide for them through the hospitality and generosity of others.\nThe clothing and equipment listed in vv. 8 and 9 provide a revealing\nglimpse of first-century dress and travel conditions. The prescriptions\nsuggest some contact with contemporary itinerant Cynic philosophers\n[Cynic Philosophers] and with the descriptions of the Israelites hastily\npreparing to leave Egypt: \u201cThis is how you shall eat it: your loins\ngirded, your sandals on your feet, and your staff in your hand\u201d\n194\n[v_Mrk_6_1] [v_Mrk_6_2] [v_Mrk_6_3] [v_Mrk_6_4] [v_Mrk_6_5] [v_Mrk_6_6] [v_Mrk_6_7] [v_Mrk_6_8] [v_Mrk_6_9] [v_Mrk_6_10] [v_Mrk_6_11] [v_Mrk_6_12] [v_Mrk_6_13] [v_Mrk_6_14] [v_Mrk_6_15] [v_Mrk_6_16] [v_Mrk_6_17] [v_Mrk_6_18] [v_Mrk_6_19] [v_Mrk_6_20] [v_Mrk_6_21] [v_Mrk_6_22] [v_Mrk_6_23] [v_Mrk_6_24] [v_Mrk_6_25] [v_Mrk_6_26] [v_Mrk_6_27] [v_Mrk_6_28] [v_Mrk_6_29] [v_Mrk_6_30] [v_Mrk_6_31] [v_Mrk_6_32] [v_Mrk_6_33] [v_Mrk_6_34] [v_Mrk_6_35] [v_Mrk_6_36] [v_Mrk_6_37] [v_Mrk_6_38] [v_Mrk_6_39] [v_Mrk_6_40] [v_Mrk_6_41] [v_Mrk_6_42] [v_Mrk_6_43] [v_Mrk_6_44] [v_Mrk_6_45] [v_Mrk_6_46] [v_Mrk_6_47] [v_Mrk_6_48] [v_Mrk_6_49] [v_Mrk_6_50] [v_Mrk_6_51] [v_Mrk_6_52] [v_Mrk_6_53] [v_Mrk_6_54] [v_Mrk_6_55] [v_Mrk_6_56] Mark 6:1-56\n[v_Exo_12_11] (Exod 12:11; cf. Deut 8:4; 29:5-6).5 If traveling with a staff and\nbeggar\u2019s bag had become associated with the Cynic lifestyle in popular\nthought, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` may have been requiring his disciples to maintain an\neven more radical freedom from possessions.6 His intent is that the dis-\nciples should trust in God\u2019s provision for their needs, lead lives\nconsistent with their message, and cultivate community by depending\non the provision of hospitality wherever they go. If this is the case, we\nmay infer something of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`\u2019 dress and manner of life from these\ninstructions. He apparently expected the disciples to continue to live\n[v_Jhn_12_6] and travel as he did (see the reference to the money bag in John `[char_John_Ref]` 12:6)\nand repeat the teachings on the kingdom they had learned from him.\nNevertheless, because Exodus parallels figure prominently in the rest of",
    "James W. Knox": "). That is what Christ did for this man. We are not surprised to read that one who has been the recipient of such grace would desire to follow Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` wherever He might lead.",
    "John Trapp": "When lust hath conceived ] As the plot of all diseases lies in the humours of the body; so of all sin, in the lust of the soul. There is in it a \u03c0\u03b1\u03bd\u03c3\u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03bc\u03b9\u03b1, a tacit consent, a seed plot of all sin. { a } The Papists say (but falsely) that it is the smallest of all sins, not deserving any more of God\u2019s wrath than only a want of his beatific presence, and that too without any pain or sorrow of mind from the apprehension of so great a loss. There are also of ours that say, That it is not forbidden by the law; but sure we are, it is cursed and condemned (and therefore forbidden) by the law. { a } Empedoclis vocabulum apud Aristot.\nVer.\n15. When lust hath conceived] As the plot of all diseases lies in the humours of the body; so of all sin, in the lust of the soul. There is in it a \u03c0\u03b1\u03bd\u03c3\u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03bc\u03b9\u03b1, a tacit consent, a seed plot of all sin. {a} The Papists say (but falsely) that it is the smallest of all sins, not deserving any more of God\u2019s wrath than only a want of his beatific presence, and that too without any pain or sorrow of mind from the apprehension of so great a loss. There are also of ours that say, That it is not forbidden by the law; but sure we are, it is cursed and condemned (and therefore forbidden) by the law. {a} Empedoclis vocabulum apud Aristot.\nVer.\n15. In all manner of conversation ] Our very civilities must savour of sanctity, and our common conversation relish of religion. St Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]`\u2019s civil conversation, \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5\u03c5\u03bc\u03b1, was in heaven, #Php 3:20 . Holiness must be written upon our bridles when we war; upon our cups when we drink, #Zec 14:20,21 . It is said of a certain Scotch divine, that he did even eat, and drink, and sleep eternal life.\nVer.\n15. In all manner of conversation] Our very civilities must savour of sanctity, and our common conversation relish of religion. St Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]`\u2019s civil conversation, \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5\u03c5\u03bc\u03b1, was in heaven, #Php 3:\n15. After my decease ] Gr. \u03b5\u03be\u03bf\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd, my exodus, or passage to heaven. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` apostle in this expression hath respect doubtless to that, #Lu 9:31 Da 6:15 , refers to #Ps 2:1 . To have these things always, &amp;c. ] Dilexi virum (said Theodosius concerning Ambrose), I could not but love the man exceedingly for this, that when he died he was more solicitous of the Churches than of his own dangers. And I am in no less care (saith Cicero) what the commonwealth will do when I am dead, than while I am yet alive. Luther in many places of his books tells us, he was much afraid that the true doctrine of justification by faith alone would be, after his death, much defaced if not utterly lost out of the Church. And it happened out accordingly in part, by the pestilent opinions and endeavours of Flacius, Osiander, and other busy broachers of errors, about that fundamental point. While Luther lived, they forbore to vent themselves. But when his head was laid, Osiander was heard to boast Leonem mortuum esse; vulpes a se flocci pendi: that the lion was dead; and for the foxes (meaning Melancthon and the rest), he cared not for them. (Melch. in Vit. Osiand.)\nVer.\n15. After my decease] Gr. \u03b5\u03be\u03bf\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd, my exodus, or passage to heaven. The apostle in this expression hath respect doubtless to [v_Luk_9_31] that, #Lu 9:31 Da 6:15, refers to #Ps 2:"
