    "James W. Knox": "). Rather than sail the seas and travel the earth with the one who made him whole, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` bids the man return to the place of his upbringing and tell his family and friends what the Lord had done for him. This has been taught countless times since the Holy Spirit had it written as an example to all those who are newly saved by the God of all grace. Go and tell your family. Go and tell your friends. Thus it should be. But we would do well to spy out a marvelous truth found in the cross-reference given in Luke",
    "John Trapp": "Swift to hear ] Reaching after that word of truth, the gospel, #Jas 1:18 , and drinking it in as the dry earth doth the dew of heaven. Life doth now enter into the soul at the ear, as at first death did, #Ge 3:19 Slow to speak ] We read often, \"He that hath an ear to hear, let him hear\"; but never, he that hath a tongue to speak, let him speak; for this we can do fast enough, without bidding. But hath not Nature taught us the same that the apostle here doth, by giving us two ears, and those open; and but one tongue, and that hedged in with teeth and lips? It is also tied and bound fast by the root, and hath for guides and counsellors the brain above and the heart beneath it. Hence your wisest men are most silent; for they know that as some gravel and mud passeth away with much water, so in many words there lacketh not sin. Slow to wrath ] Slow to snuff at those that reprove you. { See Trapp on \"Heb 13:22\" } Rage not when touched, though to the quick.\nVer.\n19. Swift to hear] Reaching after that word of truth, the gospel, #Jas 1:18, and drinking it in as the dry earth doth the dew of heaven. Life doth now enter into the soul at the ear, as at first [v_Gen_3_19] death did, #Ge 3:19 Slow to speak] We read often, \"He that hath an ear to hear, let him hear\"; but never, he that hath a tongue to speak, let him speak; for this we can do fast enough, without bidding. But hath not Nature taught us the same that the apostle here doth, by giving us two ears, and those open; and but one tongue, and that hedged in with teeth and lips? It is also tied and bound fast by the root, and hath for guides and counsellors the brain above and the heart beneath it. Hence your wisest men are most silent; for they know that as some gravel and mud passeth away with much water, so in many words there lacketh not sin. Slow to wrath] Slow to snuff at those that reprove you. {See Trapp on [v_Heb_13_22] \"Heb 13:22\"} Rage not when touched, though to the quick.\nVer.\n19. Without blemish ] Of original pollution. And without spot ] Of actual sin: or thus, without blemish, that is, sound within; and without spot, right in the outward parts. A lamb may be fair without that is rotten within. Christ was none such, but a complete sacrifice for sin.\nVer.\n19. Without blemish] Of original pollution. And without spot] Of actual sin: or thus, without blemish, that is, sound within; and without spot, right in the outward parts. A lamb may be fair without that is rotten within. Christ was none such, but a complete sacrifice for sin.\nVer.\n19. A more sure word ] The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` authority of the Scriptures is greater than an angel\u2019s voice, of equal command to God\u2019s audible and immediate voice, and of greater perspicuity and certainty to us; for besides inspiration, it is both written and sealed. As unto a light ] As the governor of a ship hath his hand on the stern, his eye on the pole star; so should we on Christ the day star, #Re 2:28 22:12 . Until the day dawn ] Till there be a more full gospel light. And the day star ] Christ the star of Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`, the bright morning star, #Re 22:16 , the Sun of righteousness, #Mal 4:2\nVer.\n19. A more sure word] The authority of the Scriptures is greater than an angel\u2019s voice, of equal command to God\u2019s audible and immediate voice, and of greater perspicuity and certainty to us; for besides inspiration, it is both written and sealed. As unto a light] As the governor of a ship hath his hand on the stern, his eye on the pole star; so should we on Christ the day star, [v_Rev_2_28] #Re 2:28 22:\n19. That censure passed on him by Erasmus is very right; Si legas, &c.: If thou read Seneca as a pagan, he wrote Christianly; but if as a Christian, he wrote paganishly.\nVer."
