    "James D. Nogalski, James W Knox": "If any man among you seem to be religious, etc.] By his\npreaching, or praying, and hearing, and other external duties of religion, he\nis constant in the observance of; and who, upon the account of these\nthings, \u201cthinks himself to be a religious man\u201d, as the Vulgate Latin, Syriac,\nand Arabic versions render it; or is thought to be so by others:\nand bridleth not his tongue; but boasts of his works, and speaks ill of his\nbrethren; backbites them, and hurts their names and characters, by private\ninsinuations, and public charges without any foundation; who takes no care\nof what he says, but gives his tongue a liberty of speaking anything, to the\ninjury of others, and the dishonour of God, and his ways: there seems to be\n[v_Psa_39_1] an allusion to (<193901>\nBut deceiveth his own heart; with his show of religion, and external\nperformances; on which he builds his hopes of salvation; of which he is\nconfident; and so gives himself to a loose way of talking what he pleases:\nthis man's religion is vain; useless, and unprofitable to himself and others;\nall his preaching, praying, hearing, and attendance on the ordinances will be\nof no avail to him; and he, notwithstanding these, by his evil tongue, brings\na scandal and reproach upon the ways of God, and doctrines of Christ.\nVer.",
    "James W. Knox": "In the first place, the good gent had to dispose all mention of salvation by grace to have so tragically erred in setting forth the means by which salvation is affected. Secondly, there is no mention of baptism anywhere in Titus, much less in Titus 3:\n26. Yet once the individual has bought into the idea that the learned man, not the word of God, is the final authority, the grace of God becomes a handful of water. Those who object are called hateful. Not every new Bible has the Vatican rendering of\n26. In the first place, the good gent had to dispose all mention of salvation by grace to have so tragically erred in setting forth the means by which salvation is affected. Secondly, there is no mention [v_Tit_3_5] of baptism anywhere in Titus, much less in Titus 3:\n26. Yet once the individual has bought into the idea that the learned man, not the word of God, is the final authority, the grace of God becomes a handful of water. Those who object are called hateful. Not every new Bible has the Vatican rendering of",
    "John Trapp": "Seem to be religious ] There is a great deal of this seemingness now abroad: Aliud in titulo, aliud in pyxide. Verba tua Dei plane sunt, facta veto Diaboli, as one told Pope Innocent III: You speak like a God, but do like a devil; a fair professor, but a foul sinner. The form of religion is honos; the power onus. Many do but act it, play it: they do no more than assume it, as the angels did the dead bodies without a soul to animate them, or as Jeroboam\u2019s wife put on her demure apparel when she was to go to the prophet. The mere seemer is a fraud, #Job 13:16 , imposturam facit et patitur: fumum vendidit, fumo peribit. He is like the painted grapes that deceived the living birds, saith one, or the golden apples with this motto, \"No further than colour\"; touch them and they vanish. But deceiveth ] The heart first deceiveth us with colours, and when we are once doting after sin, then we join and deceive our hearts by fallacious reasonings.\nVer.\n26. Seem to be religious] There is a great deal of this seemingness now abroad: Aliud in titulo, aliud in pyxide. Verba tua Dei plane sunt, facta veto Diaboli, as one told Pope Innocent III: You speak like a God, but do like a devil; a fair professor, but a foul sinner. The form of religion is honos; the power onus. Many do but act it, play it: they do no more than assume it, as the angels did the dead bodies without a soul to animate them, or as Jeroboam\u2019s wife put on her demure apparel when she was to go to the prophet. The [v_Job_13_16] mere seemer is a fraud, #Job 13:16, imposturam facit et patitur: fumum vendidit, fumo peribit. He is like the painted grapes that deceived the living birds, saith one, or the golden apples with this motto, \"No further than colour\"; touch them and they vanish. But deceiveth] The heart first deceiveth us with colours, and when we are once doting after sin, then we join and deceive our hearts by fallacious reasonings.\nVer.\n26. Received by tradition] Children are very apt to follow their parents\u2019 example, whether of good or evil. Me ex ea opinione quam a maioribus accepi de cultu Deorum, nullius unquam movebit oratio, saith Cicero, I will never forsake that way of di vine service that I have received from my fore fathers.\nVer."
