    "James W. Knox": "The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` Lord\u2019s enemies thought themselves in God\u2019s stead and sought to apply this principle to Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` (Luke 20:26), but failed. Many readers might think it strange to find the words of the Lord used in this context. Yet God\u2019s words will save a man or damn a man \u2014 depending on the man\u2019s response. If one will not receive the word, the word will take hold of such a one. (See Deuteronomy 28:15, 45.) 1:6 They returned and said. This could be the answer of the fathers to the former prophets or the answer of Zechariah\u2019s hearers to his present message. In either case, we have the same sad outcome. First, there is the inevitable principle of sowing and reaping. God did not deal with them according to another man\u2019s sins or another nation\u2019s transgressions but gave each of them what they had merited by their own doings. (Compare Lamentations 2:17.) Second, there seems to be a resignation to their fate. They were told to repent so that when their time of chastening would be completed, they might once again enjoy the blessings of the Lord. They returned to the prophet and said, in so many words, that if repentance would not negate due chastening, then there is no point in repenting. Like so many, they had fallen into sin by \u201cliving for the moment\u201d and could not see the future gain in turning to the Lord. 1:4-6 So hath he dealt with us. These verses are the foundation principles of Zechariah\u2019s mission. They set forth: The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` condition of all blessing. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` evils of disobedience. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` immutable, unchangeable word of God. God ever dealing with His people in government according to their ways and doings. These four principles are consistent through every dispensation. This second section of Zechariah, running from 1:7 through 6:8, contains a series of eight visions. Summary of the Visions The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` Rider (1:7-17) \u2014 God has not forgotten Jerusalem, but there is an evident need of divine interference on behalf of the people. They are given strong assurance that this need shall be provided. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` Horns and Carpenters (1:18-21) \u2014 God will destroy Israel\u2019s enemies. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` Surveyor (2:1-13) \u2014 Jerusalem will be restored. Promises great enlargement and absolute security. Joshua the High Priest (3:1-10) \u2014 The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` nation will be cleansed. Exhibits forgiveness of the sin that had been the cause of all the previous troubles. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` Candlestick and the Trees (4:1-14) \u2014 God\u2019s power will enable Joshua and Zerubbabel to finish their task. This serves as a counterpart to the fourth vision by promising positive communication of God\u2019s Spirit and grace, which secure sanctification and justification. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` Flying Roll (5:1-4) \u2014 This guards against a perversion of the two previous visions (as if they warranted security) on the part of the impenitent by exhibiting the fearful course of God upon all sinners. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` Woman (5:5-11) \u2014 Wickedness is carried from the promised land to Babylon. This vision further enforces the point of the sixth by representing a longer, yet more dreadful, deportation than that to Babylon awaited unfaithful Israel. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` War Chariots (6:1-8) \u2014 God controls the nations. Jerusalem is safe. This completes the series of visions in an artistic manner by returning to the point whence they set out and by repeating much the same imagery as in the first. It shows accomplishment of all that which the first image promised. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` First Vision 1:7 Sebat. This is the Chaldean or Syriac name for the eleventh month on the Hebrew calendar. It corresponds to our January-February. 1:7 The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` four and twentieth day of the eleventh month. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` date given in 1:7 shows that three months have passed since the warning (not to follow in the footsteps of their fathers) was given the people. 1:7 Sebat \u2026 Darius. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` occasion of these visions was peculiar. The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` Persian Empire considerably favored the Jews. Consequently, there were two things necessary to communicate to the Lord\u2019s chosen: The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` Lord wanted them to see that He had turned the heart of this king that they might enjoy this favor. Therefore, they were not indebted to the earthly monarch, but to their God for all blessings. Both of these points are seen in\n23. The Lord\u2019s enemies thought themselves in God\u2019s stead and [v_Luk_20_26] sought to apply this principle to Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` (Luke 20:26), but failed. Many readers might think it strange to find the words of the Lord used in this context. Yet God\u2019s words will save a man or damn a man \u2014 depending on the man\u2019s response. If one will not receive the word, the word will take hold of such a one. (See Deuteronomy 28:15, 45.) 1:6They returned and said. This could be the answer of the fathers to the former prophets or the answer of Zechariah\u2019s hearers to his present message. In either case, we have the same sad outcome. First, there is the inevitable principle of sowing and reaping. God did not deal with them according to another man\u2019s sins or another nation\u2019s transgressions but gave each of them what they [v_Lam_2_17] had merited by their own doings. (Compare Lamentations 2:17.) Second, there seems to be a resignation to their fate. They were told to repent so that when their time of chastening would be completed, they might once again enjoy the blessings of the Lord. They returned to the prophet and said, in so many words, that if repentance would not negate due chastening, then there is no point in repenting. Like so many, they had fallen into sin by \u201cliving for the moment\u201d and could not see the future gain in turning to the Lord. 1:4-6So hath he dealt with us. These verses are the foundation principles of Zechariah\u2019s mission. They set forth:",
    "John Trapp": "His natural face ] Gr. the face of his nativity, that wherewith he was born into the world. Pythagoras wished his scholars often to view themselves in a glass, that if they were well-favoured, they might likewise be well-conditioned; as if otherwise, they might make it up in virtue. \u201c Si mihi difficilis formam natura negavit, Ingenio formae damna rependo meae.\u201d Ovid. Epist. The law is a crystal glass, wherein a man may soon see his spiritual deformities, and be advertised of his duty. { See Trapp on \"Jas 1:25\" }\nVer.\n23. His natural face] Gr. the face of his nativity, that wherewith he was born into the world. Pythagoras wished his scholars often to view themselves in a glass, that if they were well- favoured, they might likewise be well-conditioned; as if otherwise, they might make it up in virtue. \u201c Si mihi difficilis formam natura negavit, Ingenio formae damna rependo meae.\u201d Ovid. Epist. The law is a crystal glass, wherein a man may soon see his spiritual deformities, and be advertised of his duty. {See Trapp on \"Jas 1:25\"}\nVer.\n23. Born again ] A man shall never have occasion to curse the day of his new birth. By the word of God ] Made prolific and generative by the Spirit, #1Jo 3:9 . It is the Father that regenerateth us originally, #Tit 3:5 , the Son meritoriously and effectively, #Joh 14:19 Eph 5:26 ; the Holy Ghost consummately and applicatorily, through faith wrought and increased in us by the word and sacraments, #Jas 1:18 Ac 22:16 \"Be baptized, and wash away thy sins,\" i.e. be renewed.\nVer.\n23. Born again] A man shall never have occasion to curse the day of his new birth. By the word of God] Made prolific and generative by the Spirit, #1Jo 3:"
